Suffolk, England":"West Stow, Suffolk, England","Blisworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Blisworth, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aspall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspull in Greater Manchester, named from Old English <i>æspe</i> ‘aspen’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Asbell  .","Irish: in Ireland, this is usually the English name in 1 above imported, but according to MacLysaght it is also an east Leinster variant of   Archbold   (see   Archibald  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Asbell","meanings":["Altered form of English   Aspell  . Compare   Asbill  ,   Azbell  , and   Azbill  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":20,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":29,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Aspall was born in 1308, in Lackford, Suffolk, England, his father, Sir Robert de Aspall, was 34 and his mother, Alice Cressingham, was 24. He married Mirabel Wake from 8 April 1336 to 10 March 1337, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in June 1355, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1308–June 1355":"1308–juuni 1355","1304–1357":"1304–1357","1308–1355":"1308–1355","1320–1372":"1320–1372","1307–1355":"1307–1355","1332–1377":"1332–1377","1274–1327":"1274–1327","1285–1338":"1285–1338","1285":"1285","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1327":"1327","from 8 April 1336 to 10 March 1337":"8. aprill 1336 kuni 10. märts 1337","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","June 1355":"juuni 1355","after 1338":"pärast 1338","1357":"1357","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1308":"1308","1307":"1307"